    "input": "30-year-old male construction worker presents to the outpatient clinic with a 4‑day history of fever (recorded at home this morning as 38.8 °C), headache, malaise, and a progressive vesicular rash that began on his face and spread to his trunk and limbs. He was diagnosed with monkeypox after PCR from a lesion sample. He reports feeling hot and sweaty, with a mild sore throat but denies cough, chest pain, shortness of breath, or abdominal pain. He says he drinks plenty of water but still feels warm, and mentions that he works outdoors in the heat, often lifting heavy equipment, which adds to his discomfort. He has no known drug allergies, no chronic illnesses, and is not currently taking any medications. He notes that his roommate developed a similar rash about a week ago. Vital signs at the clinic: temperature 38.7 °C, heart rate 96 bpm, blood pressure 128/78 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO₂ 98 % on room air. Physical examination reveals multiple 2–3 mm vesicular lesions on the face, neck, and extremities, some with pustular crusting, and mild cervical lymphadenopathy. The patient is awaiting further management."
}

{
